Implats Limited | Europe
Unchanged Impact to our thesis
In- line Financial results versus consensus
Modest revision lower Direction of next 12- month consensus EPS
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

A well guided set of numbers post the 4 August production/costs update and 11 August trading statement. Today Implats is reporting HEPS of RO.85/share marginally above the mid- point of the guidance range per the trading statement. At first look the delta to our original estimates does appear to have been driven by the adverse impact of lower sales volumes and higher unit costs (as expected) coupled with a high effective tax rate \((53\%)\) . Implats have declared a final dividend of R1.65/ share (R1.5bn) ahead of both MSE RO.99/share and company compiled consensus median of RO.50/share. After including dividends paid to Impala Chrome minorities this equates to \(\sim 60\%\) of FY25 adjusted FCF (policy minimum \(30\%\) of FCF). The payout appears to be premised on both the robust balance sheet position (R8.1bn net cash on had) and improving market conditions.

FY26 guidance - production in- line, destock now over 4 years, unit cost guidance above MSE: Group concentrate production of 3.4- 3.6m PGM oz (MSE 3.64m oz, the primary difference to our numbers arises from wind down of Impala Canada by year end) - guidance reflects expected improvements at both Zimplats and Impala Bafokeng; refined production of 3.4- 3.6m PGM oz (MSE 3.58m oz) - implying a partial destock of excess inventories in FY26 with the full destock of the 420k 6E oz expected to be completed by end FY29 (previously end FY27); unit cost guidance of R23,500- 24,500/PGM oz- or \(+4\) to \(+9\%\) y/y (above MSE R22,571/PGM oz, it appears that some of the gains from the restructuring in FY24 have been eroded away); capex of R8- 9bn (MSE R8.8bn) - previous guidance was R9bn.
Other standout comments:

FY26 has started with an improved performance at the mining operations and greater stability across the processing assets. Implats are progressing an optimized operating strategy and enhanced maintenance protocols across group furnaces All 3 major PGM markets are likely to remain in deficit in FY25 with market shortfalls increasing from prior estimates

We use a blended average of DCF and forward multiples. Our DCF valuation is based on reserve LOM; a nominal 1/ ZAR WACC of \(16\%\) in SA and 2/USD WACC of \(10.5\%\) in North America. We use a forward EV/EBITDA multiple of \(6x\) , based on a historical sector average of \(8x\) and then adjusted to reflect 1/elevated cycle stage risk, and 2/Zimbabwe risk, higher production cost.

- Optionality through the integration of Impala Bafokeng/Rustenburg to realise synergies and increase LOM- Balance sheet strength providing a defensive buffer- Destocking post Zimplats smelter completion- High level of operating gearing to PGM basket
- More dilution in Zimbabwe- Impala Canada outsized reliance on palladium- Rustenburg/Bafokeng complex underperformance (costs, volumes, safety)

Equal-weight (E). The stock's total return is expected to be in line with the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.

Not-Rated (NR). Currently the analyst does not have adequate conviction about the stock's total return relative to the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.

Underweight (U). The stock's total return is expected to be below the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.
